# Java API Misconfiguration Vulnerability

## Executive Summary
Improper configuration of the standard Java API for XML parsing (`javax.xml.parsers.DocumentBuilderFactory`) can lead to XML External Entity (XXE) injection vulnerabilities in web applications. If not explicitly secured, the default API implementation will process external entities, allowing attackers to read local server files, execute Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF), and potentially cause denial-of-service (DoS) attacks.

## Details
When processing untrusted XML payloads from web requests (such as SOAP services, SAML assertions, or REST endpoints accepting `application/xml`), the XML parser must be instructed to ignore DTDs (Document Type Definitions) and external entities. The default behavior of Java's `DocumentBuilderFactory` resolves these entities automatically.

### Vulnerable and Secure Implementations

```java
import javax.xml.parsers.DocumentBuilderFactory;
import javax.xml.parsers.DocumentBuilder;
import org.w3c.dom.Document;
import java.io.InputStream;

public class VulnerableXmlParser {

    public Document parseUserData(InputStream xmlInput) throws Exception {
        // Vulnerable: Using default DocumentBuilderFactory without disabling external entities allows XXE
        DocumentBuilderFactory factory = DocumentBuilderFactory.newInstance();

        DocumentBuilder builder = factory.newDocumentBuilder();

        // The parser will automatically fetch and evaluate external entities provided in xmlInput
        return builder.parse(xmlInput);
    }
}
```

***

```java
import javax.xml.parsers.DocumentBuilderFactory;
import javax.xml.parsers.DocumentBuilder;
import org.w3c.dom.Document;
import java.io.InputStream;

public class SecureXmlParser {

    public Document parseUserData(InputStream xmlInput) throws Exception {
        DocumentBuilderFactory factory = DocumentBuilderFactory.newInstance();

        // Secure: Explicitly configure the API to disable DTDs entirely
        factory.setFeature("http://apache.org/xml/features/disallow-doctype-decl", true);

        // Secure: Disable external general and parameter entities as a defense-in-depth measure
        factory.setFeature("http://xml.org/sax/features/external-general-entities", false);
        factory.setFeature("http://xml.org/sax/features/external-parameter-entities", false);

        // Secure: Prevent external DTDs from being loaded and disable entity expansion
        factory.setFeature("http://apache.org/xml/features/nonvalidating/load-external-dtd", false);
        factory.setXIncludeAware(false);
        factory.setExpandEntityReferences(false);

        DocumentBuilder builder = factory.newDocumentBuilder();

        // Safe parsing of user data; external entities will throw a SAXParseException
        return builder.parse(xmlInput);
    }
}
```

### Why the secured approach works
By invoking `setFeature()` on the `DocumentBuilderFactory` instance, we explicitly override the API's default unsafe behaviors. Setting `disallow-doctype-decl` to `true` is the most critical step, as it entirely prevents the parser from processing DTDs, which are the root cause of XXE injection. The additional features serve as a defense-in-depth mechanism to disable other potential entity expansion attacks (such as the "Billion Laughs" attack).

